### prompt
Write a function called is_odd(number) that takes in one argument (one number as input) and returns True if that number is odd. Then execute the line "print is_odd(10)" to test if your function works.
### solution
def is_odd(number):
  return number % 2 == 1
print is_odd(10)
### test
print is_odd(3)
print is_odd(5)
print is_odd(6)
print is_odd(2)
print is_odd(1)


### hint
The syntax to check and print if one  number is divisible by 3 is
<pre> print 5 % 3 == 0 # this will return False since 5 mod 3 is equal to 2. % just returns the remainder when dividing
print 6 % 3 == 0 # this will return True since 6 mod 3 is equal to 0.
</pre>
The syntax to define a function called returnTrue that always returns True is
<pre> def returnTrue():
   return True
</pre>

